1 SOUR Nguyễn thị Hương Giang, Nguyễn thị Hương Bình
1 NOTE From Nguyễn thị Hương Giang.........
2 CONT Being the 1st born son, had to fend for his family who was very poor at
2 CONC  the time.  His first job was as a coolie in a French mine in Cao Bàng.
2 CONC   To get up the courage to approach the mine's foreman to ask for a job
2 CONC  in French, he stood on a small hill overlooking the mine, and ate in o
2 CONC ne whole go, 5 corn on the cob.  Apparently, that worked.  He got his f
2 CONC irst job.  And quickly moved up to the position of foreman himself, ver
2 CONC y much trusted and liked by the French management.  Prior to 1854, a pi
2 CONC cture showed him dressed up in a suit, and dining on steak and wine wit
2 CONC h a French person.  Probably, his friend, Mr. Reynaud, who later was th
2 CONC e sole conduit between Năng and his family when they were separated in 
2 CONC 1954.  Nang, and his two older sons, Thắng and Thành, went to the South
2 CONC , whereas the rest o Năng's family stayed back in the North.  The reaso
2 CONC ning was Năng's wife, Tín, had to stay back to guard their numerous pro
2 CONC perties, which at that time consisted of 10 villas which Năng had built
2 CONC , one for each son.
2 CONT After the move to the south, Năng never remarried.  He started a flower
2 CONC  farm in Đà Lạt for a while, but then had to move to Sài gòn because of
2 CONC  communist activities in the region.
2 CONT In Sài gòn, he lived with his first born son, Thắng and Thàng's family,
2 CONC  in a 2 story villa off Công Lý's stree (now Nam Ky Khoi Nghia).  He sm
2 CONC oked and liked to putter around with woodwork.  He lived on the 2nd flo
2 CONC or, and had a beautiful plant of red bougainvillea overlooking his balc
2 CONC ony.  Prior to 1967, when fireworks were still allowed, Năng would set 
2 CONC off red firecrackers from his balcony, laying a thick carpet of red dye
2 CONC  paper on the small ground floor entrance in front of the garage.
2 CONT April 1975, Năng barely escaped the communist take over of Sài gòn.by s
2 CONC queezing on a boat together with his two sons, Thắng and Thành, and Thắ
2 CONC ng's family, that would take him to a series of refugee camps to finall
2 CONC y settle in Greenwiwch, CT;
2 CONT In the US, forever and optimist, Năng would sport his dandy suits, walk
2 CONC  to the super market to buy beef tail which his daughter-in-law, Hương 
2 CONC Diệp, would cook in a stew and put in the freezer to eat every day of t
2 CONC he week.  He would also take the bus to go to the library, to the Allia
2 CONC nce Francaise, and to attend English classes.  He also liked to take pi
2 CONC ctures of himself with his grand children in the park to send back to V
2 CONC iệtnam to the rest of his family who still lived there.
2 CONT Toward the end of his life, he slowly developed glaucoma and oncoming b
2 CONC lindness.  Unable to properly care for him any longer, Thắng and his wi
2 CONC fe decided to put Năng in a nursing home in Norwalk (exit 14 on I 95) w
2 CONC here he died 3 years later.
2 CONT Every weekend, Thắng and his family would drop by for visits.  One thin
2 CONC g his granddaughter, Giang, recalled him telling her at the start of he
2 CONC r career, was you will always need to carefully record what was said an
2 CONC d done at work by writing it all down, one folder for every important e
2 CONC vent that was discussed or defined.
2 CONT End ........
2 CONT 
2 CONT From Nguyễn thị Hương Bình.........
2 CONT 
2 CONT I love my grandfather!  He was so kind to me.
2 CONT 
2 CONT I have a lot of good memories of him from when I was a child in Vietnam
2 CONC , Giang and I would go to his house after school.  We were to do our ho
2 CONC mework there.  My handwriting was not quite up to par, and Grandpa woul
2 CONC d bribe me with caramel candies if I'd try harder and improve my handwr
2 CONC iting.  Unfortunately, I hated caramel!  I didn't tell him that though.
2 CONT 
2 CONT He was ambidextrous, and I used to sit by his side and watch him draw, 
2 CONC usually roses, simultaneously with both hands.
2 CONT 
2 CONT Every year, for Tet, my family would make about 40 banh Chung, the trad
2 CONC itional Vietnamese treats for the new year.  They needed to be boiled f
2 CONC or a long time.  This was Grandpa's job, which lasted from dusk to well
2 CONC  into the night.  I'd try to stay up with him, but would invariably fal
2 CONC l asleep.  In the middle of the night, I'd wake up, and since my bedroo
2 CONC m overlooked the courtyard, I'd look down, and just see grandpa's smold
2 CONC ering pipe.  It was such a comfort to little me.
2 CONT 
2 CONT After we moved to America, he loved to take the bus around town, going 
2 CONC nowhere in particular.  He always wore a fedora with a feather tucked i
2 CONC n its band.  As far as I can tell, he was the first man who carried a “
2 CONC man-purse”.  When he got home, he would tell us about all the ladies wi
2 CONC th whom he had struck up conversations.  I always thought of him as qui
2 CONC te debonair.
2 CONT 
2 CONT One year, my parents decided to convert the attic of our one-story, two
2 CONC -bedroom house, into living spaces.  In our de-construction zeal, Thien
2 CONC  stepped through to the ceiling below in the living room.  Dad was stil
2 CONC l at work, and we knew we were in a world of trouble.  Grandpa to the r
2 CONC escue; he patched up the hole with some cardboard he found around the h
2 CONC ouse.  He did such a good job that, I swear, you couldn't tell anything
2 CONC  was amiss.  Unfortunately, when Dad got home, Mom told him what happen
2 CONC ed, and he removed Grandpa's work, and set about 'fixing' it.  He didn'
2 CONC t do as good a job as Grandpa!
2 CONT 
2 CONT Grandpa was filled with joie de vivre, and when I think of him, I alway
2 CONC s subconsciously have a smile on my face.
2 CONT 
2 CONT Binh Nguyen
2 CONT Mar 23, 2025
2 CONT 
2 CONT End .......
