2 DATE 01 AUG 2019
2 PLAC 52 Havemeyer Lane, Old Greenwich, CT 06870
2 NOTE Burried at St. Mary's Cementery in Greenwich, CT in the same plot as hi
3 CONC s wife.
1 OCCU Manager at IBM / Actuary @ Gerber
1 TITL Lieutenant General, Republic of Việt Nam
2 DATE TO 30 APR 1975
1 FAMC @F31@
1 FAMS @F28@
1 NOTE Loved to play soccer as a kid in Hà nội.  Lost a pair of brand new shoe
2 CONC s which his mother had just given him when he used them as a goal post 
2 CONC in one of his many soccer games.
2 CONT Attended lycée Albert Sarault in Hanoi where he obtained first prize in
2 CONC  math, and bacalaureat with the highest honors accorded by the French j
2 CONC ury..
2 CONT Was drafted into the French army, where he had to endure the bombing of
2 CONC  Điện Biên Phủ and the ensuing debacle in Hung Yen
2 CONT Became an officer in the south Vietnam army, and rose to the rank of Li
2 CONC eutenant General.  Quite a few pictures of him available at https://www
2 CONC .flickr.com/photos/13476480@N07/albums/72157666721316676.  This was whe
2 CONC n he was appointed Minister of Rural Development in Nguyễn Cao Kỳ's gov
2 CONC ernment to help pacify and attract communist insurgents to come over to
2 CONC  the south Vietnamese side.
2 CONT 
2 CONT Thắng met and married his wife, Hương Diệp in 1960 through the introduc
2 CONC tion of an army chaplain, Fr. Castres.  They went on to have 6 children
2 CONC , who were raised in strict discipline and the catholic faith.  Every S
2 CONC unday, the family would pile into a small army jeep, and Thắng would dr
2 CONC ive it himself to take everyone to church, followed by a visit to Diệp'
2 CONC s mother and her family at Trần Nhật Duầt street.
2 CONT 
2 CONT Thắng took a leave of absence from the Army to attend math courses at S
2 CONC aigon University of Science where one of this math teachers turned out 
2 CONC to be a communist agent.  Prior to the fall of Saigon in 1975, he went 
2 CONC to France for 4 months to try to find a cure for the persistent buzzing
2 CONC  in his ear, and stayed with his borther in law Doco and his wife in Re
2 CONC ims.
2 CONT 
2 CONT Being the first born son, Thắng took on the care of this father Năng wi
2 CONC th the help of his wife.  Năng has lived with his son practically all h
2 CONC is life in South VN, except for brief stints in Đà lạt and at Công Lý s
2 CONC t. in Saigon when Thắng moved his family to the army compound near TSN 
2 CONC airport for security reason after the Tết Mậu Thân communist attack.
2 CONT Thắng and his family, including his father and brother, were able to bo
2 CONC ard one of the last boats leaving Việt Nam when the communist army made
2 CONC  its final thrust into Saigon Arill 30th, 1975.  Thắng was the only gen
2 CONC eral in civilian clothing when the boat was accosted by US navy officer
2 CONC s of the 7th Fleet to escort them to the US base at Subic bay the Phili
2 CONC ppines.  The US officers told all the other generals to take of their m
2 CONC edals and uniforms since they no longer had a country.  Thắng in his ci
2 CONC vilian clothes was saved this shaming.
2 CONT 
2 CONT Thắng loves math, but he loved his wife Diệp more.  She passed away in 
2 CONC 2016 leaving him an old and broken man.  He goes to visit her grave sit
2 CONC e at St. Mary's cemetery every day.
2 CONT 
2 CONT From: Nguyễn Đức Thiện
2 CONT My father military life and accolades are well documented in books and 
2 CONC the internet. I will share the personal stories I have had with him.
2 CONT - When I was in Vietnam, I went to LaSalle Taberd grade school.  (now d
2 CONC efunct, located at 53 đường Nguyễn Du) One day, My dad was busied with 
2 CONC something (most likely involved with his mathematics) forgot to pick me
2 CONC  up from school for several hours. I was worried and stood against the 
2 CONC wall of the nearby Bộ Nội Vụ building until dark.
2 CONT - My brother and I were usually forced to sleep in the afternoon in Vie
2 CONC tnam. My dad always instructed us to sleep "kiểu mới", that is on our b
2 CONC ack and with our arms folded in front of us.
2 CONT - In our harrowing escape from Vietnam, I was and am very proud of my f
2 CONC ather, my hero when he with the help of his brother (chú Thành) took ca
2 CONC re of his six kids, my mom and my grandfather.
2 CONT - In the early years in the US, our family had a routine of going food 
2 CONC shopping at the local supermarket (Bon Giorno). There were always two c
2 CONC arts full of supplies for the week and the cost was around $100!
2 CONT - My dad is really smart but he wasn't very handy. When he was given a 
2 CONC car from a sum of $1, the car had problems. The gas pedal didn't have a
2 CONC  return spring so he tied a string to pull it up. When the exhaust had 
2 CONC a hole in it, he wrapped rags to stop the leak.
2 CONT - We had a large family but we lived in a small house. During the Carte
2 CONC r presidency, my dad listened to the administration and lower the therm
2 CONC ostat. The house had mold due to the lower temperature. My dad tasked m
2 CONC e to repaint the wall whenever mold appeared. That was a losing battle.
2 CONT - When my dad worked at IBM, he sometimes  went to work on the weekend 
2 CONC and some of the kids would go with him.
2 CONT - During college years, my brother and I went to Columbia University to
2 CONC gether. We took the Metro North train on fridays and my dad drove us ba
2 CONC ck almost every weekend. Sometimes my mom accompanied us and stop in Ch
2 CONC inatown to do some food shopping. My dad also liked to visit his  favor
2 CONC ite bookstores, Barnes & Noble, Strands in NY. He spent hours looking f
2 CONC or his favorites books and reading them. During the weekends, my dad ma
2 CONC de us go with him to the library to study.
